column98: This is a hands-on laboratory course that investigates the role specific genes play in handling thermal stress. Students will develop hypotheses, design experiments, and analyze their own data. Students will learn about how genes are regulated, how transgenic manipulations can alter gene regulation, and how the regulation of genes contributes to environmental adaptation.

Course description: Histology examines the microscopic anatomy of tissues.  This course uses hundreds of high-resolution images to explore the tissues of the human body, emphasizing the interplay of function and form.  We will examine healthy and diseased tissues, primarily at the light microscope level, and will also survey processes by which tissue samples are prepared and imaged.

column98:
Microbial genomics is being used to address many current medical and environmental challenges (e.g., COVID-19 pandemic, bioremediation of contaminated water). In this class, you will learn how to investigate microbial genomes and predict microbial function (e.g., metabolism, motility) through gene/protein analyses. We will predict microbial responses to environmental conditions such as viral infection (e.g., CRISPR signatures) and antibiotic exposure (e.g., resistance genes). We will apply our knowledge to analyze real microbial genome sequence data, synthesize our findings, and communicate our findings in a variety of scientific formats.
Prereq: BIOL 2051/2095, 2061/2097, 2071/2096, 2081/2098, and 3654 with a C- or higher. No prior knowledge of bioinformatics needed.
Students must have completed BIOL 3654 with a C- or higher to register for this course.

column98: Students should enroll in 1 credit hour during year one (spring and summer semesters only), 1 credit hour during year two (fall, spring, and summer semesters), and 3 credit hours during year three (fall, spring, and summer semesters).  A total of 14 credit hours of PSYC 7910 are required.  This course is intended for students in the Clinical Health Psychology PhD program.  Students may be administratively dropped if the course instructors determine that they are incorrectly enrolled.
